content: Hello everyone, welcome to the tactics lesson!
We begin with the participation check. :)

slamduk, aivo, tunnet99, yyfcsd, tieuphilac, xiebin123xie, nstxyty, Silver, hibiscus, Intotherenju, span, FTDS, Chancewu, shaoping, luwenzhe, whte, wetcat, coco_yuang, pseudonym, penitent, eastmen, scm2000, Red_Zombie, fallnavy, renjunewbie, amber, smallpig, Andry, smiling, weigui, Renjufans, Ikon, civsnail, yzhnie, shuwang, 8914643, pantrike, Morden.
Today we will begin to learn the tactics of white attack.
If white has a chance for attack,
white has bigger variety of attacking tools.
When we learned about the use of lines,
we learned the principle that we should not use the threes or fours unless we have to, or unless we clearly benefit from it/
the same goes for white side.
even if you are white, try to be wise about using the lines you have.
that is the use of forbidden moves.
white can take advantage of black's forbidden points,
yes, this is one of the most attractive parts of renju
Sometimes the forbidden move helps white to have the win immediately, by trapping the forbidden point.
sometimes, the forbidden move does not give white win,
but it gives something else useful,
such as good white stones location,
and getting those smaller benefits, white can turn the game into its favor.
and taking advantage of 3x3 at j6
black cannot play its best move to j7
black would want to play j7,
so black will play elsewhere than j7.
and that means, white will get both k6 and j6 points.
and that way white gets bigger space.
Now white has both j7 and k6 points.
black could not take this key point
If white just goes to j7,
then black can cut off white's attempt to gain more space.
But by playing here, white ensures both k6 point and j7 point.
white "took advantage of 3x3 at j6", and as a result, got two useful stones k6 and j7,
which later is enough for powerful white attack.
to use 3x3 to win directly at forbidden point.
to use 3x3 to gain key points
furthermore, white can use black's 3x3 for its own defensive purposes,
but we will study white's defense in another lesson.
i think, most of you have used 3x3 trap for direct win purposes.
black goes three and white wins
this is the direct usage of 3x3, for trapping purposes.
this is simple enough, so we do not spend much time on it.
here, one just has to count few steps forward, find win, and do it.
this is maybe not easy for beginners at first,
but with some months of renju practice,
you will be able to trap all the 3x3 which are within your reach.
i sometimes think of my childhood renju games,
one of the first ones i played.
at that time me and my club members were poor players,
and sometimes the 3x3 traps were so simple.
I remember, i played with some players same trap many times
it was my favorite trap in my early days of renju playing
nearly all club members knew the simple plan:
you are white so that you could trap them
but we actually know now its not a good move
and then all games had same ending:
well, sooner or later they all learned to distinguish the danger,
they started to play this 5th move,
and my life wasnt so easy anymore
so, from this little story you can see that every beginner will quite soon reach to the level where he can detect the danger of 3x3
and when being white, he can count the vct steps up to 3x3 trap.
so, as we know how to win when the 3x3 is just few steps away,
we can move on to second question.
how to use 3x3 when there is no vct,
or when there is no obvious structure of 3x3 ahead.
this is what brings you to the new level in renju.
it is like the people of stone age
they had to dig the big hole
but some piece of meat on it as a bait
and then wait for the beast
sometimes the beast was smart, sometime ssilly
silly beast went for the piece of meat and was trapped
some wise beast smelled the trap
next time people had to make better trap
we may begin with simplest trap ideas
and then end with advanced trapping ideas.
Well, in early days, many people played this famous trap:
it looks so much as one of the known theories,
then black gets good attack from this
and tens of people fell into this evil trap
and careless people followed same plan
the purpose of that 6th move at that time was ONLY the trap
RT,i have a simple renju like this
those players, playing that 6th move actually had no clue what to do if black didnt fall into trap
they just hoped the trap HAD TO work
today people are more educated about theory
and they can avoid easiest traps in opening stage
then some people who were scared of the trap
Then, the fans of 3x3 traps created another trap.
They took advantage of the bug in famous Japanese book,
and provoked black player to follow theory here
which actually ends with black's death.
although japanese book claimed it to be good for black.
when i was first told about that trap in Russian tournament,
i said, no way there is any trap,
then the guy, who was quite poor at skill, said,
he studied it over and over again
and he finally showed to me
this is the theory, claiming black to be good..
may you say us the guy name? :)
he doesnt play renju over 10 years already
and from that day i started to look the whole japanese book in new look
before we thought its like a bible
but then we realised it contains mistakes
and we started to study the mistakes
Time passed, and people learned nearly all opening theories
it was already impossible to trap someone just by opening theory.
so, the composition of 3x3 had to happen somewhere in the middle-game.
I start with some random examples of my previous games.
and i was sure the k10 point was safe
Missed his tactics, he was just composing the 3x3 trap there.
and i thought he was just developing in new area.
we saw this in class before :)
now my k11 stone doesnt save anymore
you had seen all todays examples in class before
under the focus of composing a trap
I think it is great to check same patterns again, from different aspect
Well, let me give you another example.
In 1997, this 7th move suddenly became popular.
At that time, i was the fan of this weird 12th move.
I was likely the only person playing this 112th move
while all the others played 12-i11 or 12-k9..
anyway, I was lucky, i won 2.5 points out of 3 games with this 12th move.
this game here is my game with Aldis Reims in WC 97.
how many of you know him?
heard of him, the strongest European at that time?
he was a very strong player...
he won email WC.. and he was twice the 3rd place in real WC
he always help you in the last round
anyway, this was my game with him
It provokes whites for immediate activity.
But to compose a forbidden move is not easy.
At first look, the i11 point looks attractive.
I guess I should have stayed calm here, but I still played aggressively,
hoping to trap 3x3 at early stage of the game.
Indeed, he has only forced move here.
If up, then i get it,.
but he is top player, he doesnt fall into such childish traps
So, of course he blocked from the bottom.
Now, i wanted to trap that 3x3 so badly.
I played here finally after thinking.
White is threatning to catch 3x3 again
white put the 16th stone to h11, directly threatning the i11 3x3 point, and at the same time creating useful pair 16_10.
So, while taking advantage of the 3x3 point, i got a useful 16_10 as a gift,
and that line has a potential to threaten the 3x3 at i6,
but then he made a great move
and all my hopes were gone.
he had just blocked all my ideas.
And this is one of the toughest moments in renju -
white usually wastes some materials and good points, and even creates black some new stuff, just in order to create 3x3 trap,
and if black succeeds to bypass the trap,
then white is much worse than before.
I started to feel bad about the situation after 17th move.
and I began to regret the 16th move.
because now the 17th stone was standing well,
it blocks all white connections, and
which means there is no danger anymore.
Furthermore, that 3x3 has now become a weapon for blacks,
allowing black to shoot out from there anytime he wants.
and in any direction he wants
and white stones are not standing well either,
black has successfully exploited its provocation,
and was now closing to pomising position.
One had to survive just a little longer.
The lower side space is really good for black,
and white had to worry great deal now.
I cannot trap that i11 anymore,
and i cannot just leave it hanging there either, can i?
so I had to deal with it.
and now white is really bad.
should white play any careless move,
then i6 is black's power point with vct
that gives white a bad pattern
and should white play four first, then L8 connection is scary.
and white gets worse and worse.
So, as I said, trying to trap 3x3 has always two sides.
One is that maybe the beast will go for meat and falls into trap.
But some beast will just sneakily eat our meat, and still run away.
eat our meat and eat us , too
So I had to play a three...
but I had no choice here.
I had to go on with the momentum that I had created.
you can lookup the word 'momentum' later.
20 was also a move which is kind of straight style.
Now I need explain my idea..
since the move 16, I was forced to stay active,
and find new ideas to keep the attack alive.
the 3x3 traps are the only good weapons,
because white has not enough lines, not enough space, not enough connections....
I was thinking, how about if trap like this,.
and finally, i have no vcf threat
then it looked even more attractive
So I asked myself a question
to go for this trap or not
but my opponent is famous Aldis Reims
he will NOT fall into such trap
he will just stop it in the middle
And he will just primitively block every three i maqke
there is usually some sense of risk of making your position worse.
So, I cannot take that risk now,
and I still need to remain active.
Trying to bluff a bit here.
I made it look as if right side wss going to become powerful
but in fact its not so strong
Now I had chance to plan a new 3x3
I made a plan of 3x3 finally..
its a trap which was hard to be noticed..
I simulated a stretch of right side force towards lower side,
which would attack to point m8..
and the vct of i5, h6, g5 also
I KNEW he would feat that j5 point,
and he would likely try to play to lower side, such as i6.
because the trap was well hidden.
one could see the j5 connection,
but one could miss the hidden 3x3 that was about to come.
And now, the final preparation of trap.
Which FORCES black to take the kiler point m8
move 24 was the preparation of the big trap
such trap takes into consideration the opponents thinking and worry
I knew he would worry of j5
so he would deal with this worry "closely"
and I didnt care if he plays i6 now or i5,
here you can agree that black has to take m8
else, white takes it and then finished
which brought white into trouble sitation
then i smartened up by 22nd move
which was silly trap and he would have noticed it,
So I had to make the trap that can work against big players.
but a good player will bypass all the traps in the opening stage.

but in 2001 WC, I played another style
Move 20 was a good timing to use the tempo, to kill right wing space,
so that black could not be active there later.
And it's a nice trap too of black gets greedy and plays outside to g12
then white takes good spot at f11
and if now black doesnt stay careful,

tieuphilac, coco_yuang, slamduk, tunnet99, span, civsnail, shuwang, Intotherenju, Chancewu, aivo, Renjufans, whte, lingdodo, smiling, Silver, fallnavy, luwenzhe, nstxyty, scm2000, smallpig, eastmen, wetcat, amitabha, Morden, amber, penitent, Padovan, yyfcsd, xiebin123xie, renjunewbie, Ikon, shaoping, pseudonym, weigui, lar880n, 8914643, yzhnie, pantrike, FIFAWORLDCUP.
For some reason, this variant was not much played as white in later games by other people.
But I still like it as white.
Now, there are 33 stones on board.
White has lots of opportunities for creativity here.
One will try to make 3x3 if possible.
So I looked for 3x3 and got some ideas.
I was thinking how to make a good use of line 26_30
it looks as a strong line for trapping purposes.
the moves I made are just a fiction.
GM yy had a similar game in email WC?
To use 3x3 trap does not always mean to force black to defend.
sometimes we create situation where we have a good point, such as g4 here,
and we dont want black to take it away from us.
so we plan a situation where white "seems" to be dangerous by making the 3x3 trap at j3.
so, the tactics of 3x3 is not always trying to make 3x3..
but trying to make opponent believe there is 3x3
and then take another good point instead
I was so happy that I got g4 point,
so I became careless with next moves.
You know, this position looks like "I dont need to think anything, the 3x3 has to come up somewhere soon"
and it makes us careless a bit
it is just the feeling in all my games
its impossble that black can stop with 41 somewhere
and I still dont have trap,
but when I looked on board after 41... amazing,
I stared at the board long time
this materials is so strong here,
it just requires one additional stone from other area
and the lower part becomes a winning place
and I knew, he would think the same way
he saw I thought a long time
and he started to belive he has a chance to survive
and he knew I was probably going to "add powers"
but bringing some upper force down,
then i get the extra pair what i needed, 42_46..
and then i would try to run towards lower side with it
i was not sure yet if it helps me or not
but at least he would worry for sure.
knowing the g5 point is like a "time bomb", waiting to explode,
and then the hidden trap came
notice, just like the last game
what's your feeling when kli put the 43rd stone to g5?
My thinking was... finally, it was about time..
how come he can keep making perfect moves
did i really miscalculate the trap
then i looked for a while before playing 44 ..
maybe a second after my move
you have learned the tactics of 3x3 in many aspects.
such as simple vct attack to trap 3x3
or using the 3x3 point to get some good key points or space or tempo...
or trying to build some simple traps, hoping the opponent misses them..
psychology is important, to know your opponent!!
or trying to create advanced traps,
which require lots of psychology and understanding of opponents thinking.
these are the levels of 3x3 tactics.
You know your own level right now.
Some day, you will reach them all.
Thank you all for lesson, see you next week!
